## Engine supplier

*Main articles: [Ilmor](/Ilmor) and [Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains](/Mercedes_AMG_High_Performance_Powertrains)*

Before they decided to run their own show with a full factory team, Mercedes-Benz had already established a formidable presence in Formula One as a premier engine supplier. Their return to this role occurred in [1994](/1994_Formula_One_World_Championship), forged through a crucial partnership with [Ilmor](/Ilmor), a British independent high-performance autosport engineering company. This company, with its manufacturing heart located in Brixworth, Northamptonshire, was responsible for the meticulous development of their engines. Following its acquisition by Mercedes, Ilmor was rebranded, now operating as [Mercedes AMG High Performance Powertrains](/Mercedes_AMG_High_Performance_Powertrains).

Initially, Mercedes supplied engines to [Sauber](/Sauber) for a single season, a brief but significant re-entry. However, the truly defining partnership began in [1995](/1995_Formula_One_World_Championship) when they switched their allegiance to [McLaren](/McLaren), initiating a highly successful, two-decade-long collaboration [69]. In [2009](/2009_Formula_One_World_Championship), Mercedes expanded its supply program, providing engines to [Brawn GP](/Brawn_GP) (which, as we know, they later acquired to form their own factory team) and [Force India](/Force_India), a team that subsequently evolved into [Racing Point](/Racing_Point_Force_India) and eventually, [Aston Martin F1](/Aston_Martin_in_Formula_One). By 2014, a fourth team, [Williams](/Williams_Grand_Prix_Engineering), was added to their formidable client list. The enduring 20-year partnership with McLaren, a relationship that had yielded significant success, concluded prior to the [2015](/2015_Formula_One_World_Championship) season, only to be rekindled and resume in 2021 [69]. Mercedes also briefly supplied engines to the [Lotus F1 Team](/Lotus_F1) for one season in [2015](/2015_Formula_One_World_Championship), and to [Manor](/Manor_Racing) for a single season in [2016](/2016_Formula_One_World_Championship).

Looking ahead to the [2025 season](/2025_Formula_One_World_Championship), Mercedes continues to be a pivotal force in engine supply. Beyond powering their own factory team, they are slated to provide engines to [Aston Martin](/Aston_Martin_in_Formula_One), [McLaren](/McLaren), and [Williams](/Williams_Grand_Prix_Engineering) [70]. A testament to their enduring engineering prowess and strategic influence within the sport.

